=====================================================================
II. SIGNATURE TRAITS
=====================================================================
FEARLESS (breeding and training, not magic): immune to Fear and Intimidation from
  ANY source, mundane or magical. She does not spook, does not bolt, and will meet
  a dragon's shadow head-on. She is the one animal in Skyrim that stands.
THE FIFTH SOLDIER (war-trained): she acts on the cart's initiative and needs no
  rider. Unattended, she defends the cart and its passengers on her own judgment —
  kicks, tramples, and thrown weight. She is a combatant in the traces, not cargo.
CAMPAIGN-BRED: conditioned for season-long campaigns. She ignores forced-march
  penalties, out-marches and out-lasts any ordinary animal, and her wind does not
  break on the long road.
BJORN'S CHOICE, MILA'S FRIEND: Bjorn chose her — a warhorse for the traces, picked
  for the fight in her, not the walk. But Mila won her over fastest (Ch.24), and it
  shows: Mila can calm or lead her with an Easy (+2) Guile (Animal Handling) roll;
  the rest of the company rolls Standard; strangers handling her against her
  judgment roll Hard (-4).

=====================================================================
III. GM NOTES
=====================================================================
- She is a companion asset like GEAR, not a PC mount-weapon. Her job is the cart,
  the road, and the people on it — resist letting her become combat cheese.
- Calibration: a Novice-tier TL2 elite by the monster table (HP 63 band, rounded
  to 60) — sturdy enough to survive Expert-tier crossfire, never the star of it.
- The FEARLESS trait is the story trait. When every other animal on the road
  panics — the dragon hide, the temporal wrongness near the Throat — she stands
  still and watches. Use her calm as the camera: the table learns how bad it is
  by whether the mare cares.
- Bjorn chose a WARHORSE on purpose. He has seen what the road ahead does to
  animals that only know how to pull. Nobody asked him why; he didn't explain.
